1
00:00:02,646 --> 00:00:19,390
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato sambha sambhu tassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato sambha sambhu tassa

2
00:00:19,774 --> 00:00:34,076
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:34,095 --> 00:00:42,508
So, as I say, this is just really just covering a few major points around this practice of metta.

4
00:00:43,703 --> 00:00:55,881
The first thing is to understand the power of intention and the role of intention in the Buddhist teachings because all the conditionings that we have in the mind begin with an intention.

5
00:00:56,481 --> 00:01:05,234
So if you think of anything that human beings have done, it always starts with some intention, whether it's the intention to fly or how to fry an egg.

6
00:01:05,516 --> 00:01:09,762
I mean, it turns up in the mind as an intention and then the mind works on it

7
00:01:10,281 --> 00:01:11,924
and then it begins to manifest.

8
00:01:11,944 --> 00:01:17,132
It manifests as some language or some action and so on.

9
00:01:17,212 --> 00:01:22,159
So our intention here is basically to develop good will.

10
00:01:23,141 --> 00:01:28,150
And so long as that remains our main intention, it's actually beginning to condition us.

11
00:01:30,754 --> 00:01:36,221
And some of you will know that desire, the Buddha said that desire was the cause of suffering.

12
00:01:36,909 --> 00:01:53,572
The English word is a bit foxing because the original Pali word really refers to those desires that are based on a self, on selfish, on pride, on thinking only of oneself, on seeking happiness in the world.

13
00:01:54,013 --> 00:01:57,618
So it's actually a desire based on wrong understanding.

14
00:01:57,716 --> 00:02:10,158
But this word desire also translates another word which can mean both a wholesome desire and an unwholesome one.

15
00:02:10,239 --> 00:02:17,532
So here the desire to develop goodwill is considered beneficial.

16
00:02:17,872 --> 00:02:22,240
So you've got to be careful with this intention and desire.

17
00:02:24,075 --> 00:02:40,633
And when an idea comes into the head laced with desire, so like you might just think tea, a cup of tea, it comes up with a desire, nothing happens at that stage, nothing has been conditioned, there's no karma, there's nothing at all.

18
00:02:41,093 --> 00:02:51,264
But as soon as that thought is empowered and becomes a train of thoughts or becomes a train of speech or an action, then you're producing something in the world.

19
00:02:51,379 --> 00:02:53,685
And that's what we mean by kamma.

20
00:02:54,385 --> 00:03:05,187
So long as we're saying, may all beings be happy, and we're actually saying it, and we're meaning it, then it's actually producing something within ourselves, something within our minds.

21
00:03:05,604 --> 00:03:09,114
And it will affect the way we speak, it's the way we relate to people and so on.

22
00:03:09,694 --> 00:03:10,557
So that's how it works.

23
00:03:10,578 --> 00:03:20,843
We're starting right, as it were, the basic psychology of conditioning ourselves, conditioning the heart and mind to think goodwill.

24
00:03:21,406 --> 00:03:21,605
That's it.

25
00:03:25,837 --> 00:03:34,527
For those of you who practice vipassana, it's important because vipassana tends to create a very objective stance within us.

26
00:03:35,429 --> 00:03:39,513
And it's that equanimity that we need in order to investigate.

27
00:03:40,133 --> 00:03:43,598
But equanimity can very easily corrupt into indifference.

28
00:03:45,079 --> 00:03:55,491
And I like to tell my usual story, especially for those who haven't heard it, about the time I was in a particular monastery and there was a

29
00:03:55,471 --> 00:04:04,346
I was with a monk, and there was a cat, and he'd obviously by now killed the mouse, but he was the sort of cat that definitely didn't need a mouse.

30
00:04:04,366 --> 00:04:06,530
I mean, it was definitely overweight.

31
00:04:07,270 --> 00:04:10,015
So I said, didn't you stop that, you see?

32
00:04:10,717 --> 00:04:13,741
And the monk replied, no, it was cat karma and mouse karma.

33
00:04:14,943 --> 00:04:18,389
So I said, well, that's fine, you see, I didn't say anything.

34
00:04:18,622 --> 00:04:27,961
Anyway, I was at another monastery, this completely different time, I can't remember the sequence of how long it was, but I was sitting with a group of monks, and a cat jumped out and caught this bird.

35
00:04:29,124 --> 00:04:37,240
And this monk, as quick as a flash, came up and just gave this cat one hell of a bat, and then picked up the bird and lifted it and realised it had been killed.

36
00:04:37,625 --> 00:04:44,451
and just lifted it very beautifully by the wings into the air and chanted anicca-vatasanka, all compounded things arise and pass away.

37
00:04:45,372 --> 00:04:59,067
And of course the difference between, and that cat also didn't need a bird, and of course the difference was that the second monk recognized that his awareness was part of their karma also.

38
00:04:59,687 --> 00:05:01,810
Now that engagement doesn't take place

39
00:05:02,144 --> 00:05:03,485
unless you've got metta.

40
00:05:03,846 --> 00:05:16,180
No matter how wise you are in terms of your understanding of the Dharma, it won't actually move, engage wise, unless there's some movement in the heart as an attitude.

41
00:05:17,401 --> 00:05:22,427
Now, some traditions, like the Zen, will say, of course, that with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

42
00:05:22,829 --> 00:05:24,571
And I believe that's true.

43
00:05:24,971 --> 00:05:28,095
But I think it's good to just move it along a bit.

44
00:05:28,115 --> 00:05:30,598
That's basically what metta is doing.

45
00:05:30,814 --> 00:05:35,201
So it's an antidote really to indifference that can arise with vipassana.

46
00:05:38,607 --> 00:05:47,218
Yeah, just as an aside, a woman came to me and said that whenever she sat her partner would complain that he felt she was cold and non-communicative after sitting.

47
00:05:48,762 --> 00:05:50,865
So I said, so what do you do at the end of a sit?

48
00:05:51,285 --> 00:05:51,865
Well, just get up.

49
00:05:52,567 --> 00:05:55,692
It's nice, you've got to do metta, see, and do it to your partner too.

50
00:05:56,312 --> 00:05:58,254
so that you sort of re-engage, you see.

51
00:05:58,815 --> 00:06:01,598
She never came back, so I presume everything's all right.

52
00:06:03,459 --> 00:06:04,701
Didn't end in divorce, did it?

53
00:06:08,665 --> 00:06:18,334
So this re-engagement through metta, through attitude, begins to express itself in our eightfold path into right speech, right action, and then right livelihood.

54
00:06:19,315 --> 00:06:22,218
So it's something that saturates our lives eventually.

55
00:06:24,341 --> 00:06:29,529
The next thing is not to confuse it with other forms of love, because we use the word love for everything.

56
00:06:29,550 --> 00:06:33,115
You know, you love ice cream, for heaven's sake.

57
00:06:33,757 --> 00:06:40,567
It's not to be confused with, obviously with erotic love, because that's very specific.

58
00:06:41,608 --> 00:06:46,677
You tend to only have erotic feelings towards particular people.

59
00:06:46,716 --> 00:06:48,459
Whereas the love we're doing is universal.

60
00:06:48,742 --> 00:06:57,177
And it's also not really to do with touching the essential nature of humankind.

61
00:06:57,257 --> 00:07:01,824
It's only really working with physical attributes.

62
00:07:01,845 --> 00:07:03,187
I mean, it's got its role, obviously.

63
00:07:04,129 --> 00:07:05,891
Same with romance.

64
00:07:06,091 --> 00:07:08,274
That is also very particular.

65
00:07:08,776 --> 00:07:13,985
And it's not to be confused with metta.

66
00:07:14,026 --> 00:07:21,119
Romance is a whole set of different emotions and a type of relationship which is frankly exclusive.

67
00:07:21,139 --> 00:07:21,720
You can't be

68
00:07:22,139 --> 00:07:26,004
It'd exhaust you if you were romantically, neurotically in love with every human being you came across.

69
00:07:26,064 --> 00:07:29,951
You'd be dead very quickly.

70
00:07:32,113 --> 00:07:34,117
But it's also not to be confused with attachment.

71
00:07:34,697 --> 00:07:40,586
Now, you've got to be careful here because sometimes we think we can fall into a rather...

72
00:07:42,017 --> 00:07:46,507
a very negative thing about attachment, but attachments are natural so long as we have a self.

73
00:07:46,867 --> 00:07:50,956
You can't, you know, so long as the self is there, there's going to be an attachment.

74
00:07:51,156 --> 00:07:54,824
It's just knowing the attachment and knowing how it manifests.

75
00:07:54,843 --> 00:07:58,512
So take a, the Buddha loves the image of a mother, you see.

76
00:07:58,591 --> 00:08:03,081
For him it's the mother which is one way of expressing this metta.

77
00:08:03,500 --> 00:08:13,127
Now, it's quite natural for a mother to be attached to the child, and seemingly necessary psychologically for the child to be attached to the mother.

78
00:08:13,148 --> 00:08:17,492
It's part of the growth of that child's understanding of relationships.

79
00:08:20,134 --> 00:08:29,523
And that attachment will manifest with being overly guarding of the child, demanding the child do what they want to do, rather than listening to the child.

80
00:08:29,762 --> 00:08:33,186
So in other words, the attachment always is self-centered.

81
00:08:33,301 --> 00:08:37,047
Which doesn't mean the mother doesn't love the child, it's just got this little kink in it.

82
00:08:37,869 --> 00:08:42,275
And it's up to the mother to recognise where that's manifesting, that's all.

83
00:08:42,836 --> 00:08:45,822
And then there's the antidote to doing the opposite.

84
00:08:46,182 --> 00:08:54,297
But if you're not aware of that, then the mother thinks they're doing good, but it actually can be hurting the child in some way.

85
00:08:54,277 --> 00:08:57,385
So, we mustn't look upon that as evil.

86
00:08:57,626 --> 00:08:59,753
Some people get, I think, a bit confused with that.

87
00:08:59,773 --> 00:09:01,357
They think it's evil, but it's not.

88
00:09:01,378 --> 00:09:02,220
It's just unwholesome.

89
00:09:02,802 --> 00:09:04,145
It causes suffering, but it's not.

90
00:09:04,807 --> 00:09:06,010
The intent is not evil.

91
00:09:06,412 --> 00:09:07,375
See, this is the point.

92
00:09:07,979 --> 00:09:30,325
So our love, this meta, this universal love is going beyond that sort of love that manifests with specific attachments that we have, specific relationships rather that we have, be they one of partners, marriage, sons, daughters, mother, whatever.

93
00:09:30,845 --> 00:09:59,586
close relationships will always have that degree of attachment to them and it's just knowing how the attachment manifests that liberates us from it Metta is you could you know what is it well it's basically all the virtues that you would ask of a good friend

94
00:10:01,456 --> 00:10:12,768
kindness, certain empathy, certain caring, also to be able to share your joys, to help you when you need a bit of help.

95
00:10:13,427 --> 00:10:18,013
It's just a good friend, and it's very close to the word mitra, which means friend.

96
00:10:18,033 --> 00:10:20,635
So that's the sort of attitude that we're developing.

97
00:10:22,157 --> 00:10:24,740
But of course it goes beyond that into love your enemy.

98
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:29,504
So don't confuse love your enemy with some sort of emotional delight every time you see them.

99
00:10:29,788 --> 00:10:33,154
Here, here just means not to do them any harm.

100
00:10:33,394 --> 00:10:36,279
That's a good place to start if you hate somebody.

101
00:10:38,364 --> 00:10:40,167
You determine at least you won't do them any harm.

102
00:10:42,331 --> 00:10:47,460
And it also extends to the way we treat objects.

103
00:10:47,524 --> 00:10:50,129
You know, just gently closing the door.

104
00:10:50,850 --> 00:10:55,197
Just the way we eat, you know, not to be stabbing the plate.

105
00:10:55,216 --> 00:11:01,065
I mean, consider the pain of the plate as you stab it with forks and cut into it with your knife, you know.

106
00:11:01,086 --> 00:11:03,970
And it's that sort of gentility with objects.

107
00:11:03,990 --> 00:11:07,475
Just, you know, just think how you close the fridge door.

108
00:11:09,278 --> 00:11:09,839
Catch yourself.

109
00:11:11,140 --> 00:11:14,645
See, there's no kindness towards the fridge and it does us such good service.

110
00:11:15,283 --> 00:11:19,330
So it's a case of extending that even to our actions and the way we treat objects.

111
00:11:19,690 --> 00:11:27,861
When I began with Zen Buddhism, we had to treat all our crockery and stuff as it was all mingvas.

112
00:11:28,602 --> 00:11:29,825
That's what they taught us.

113
00:11:30,184 --> 00:11:36,734
And of course it did bring, it made very clear to me anyway, how I was bashing objects about.

114
00:11:38,035 --> 00:11:42,743
And of course that mirrors a certain hardness, you might say.

115
00:11:43,059 --> 00:11:49,288
So if we can be gentle even with the simplest things of life, it's like taking care of your pennies, you know, the big ones take care of themselves.

116
00:11:51,652 --> 00:12:01,826
So when you're eating, I'll remind you of this, you know, just take your time and just see it as a process of nourishing oneself, you know, and take care of the plates.

117
00:12:06,611 --> 00:12:12,240
Metta is one of the main teachings of the Buddha.

118
00:12:12,962 --> 00:12:16,548
which, as I say, balances the process of insight.

119
00:12:16,648 --> 00:12:21,294
And the reason is that it's our basic relationship to the world.

120
00:12:21,956 --> 00:12:32,312
So by world we mean not only other people, other beings, but as we say, even objects, even plants and everything is to be treated in a gentle way.

121
00:12:33,312 --> 00:12:36,957
And that's how you can call it our default position.

122
00:12:37,198 --> 00:12:39,942
That's what we can return to with ease.

123
00:12:40,563 --> 00:12:41,485
And from there,

124
00:12:41,903 --> 00:12:46,087
These other two qualities, compassion and sympathetic joy, arise naturally.

125
00:12:46,607 --> 00:12:56,759
So if you have a certain meta-love for somebody, obviously if they fall ill or something, the idea of wanting to help them just arises naturally.

126
00:12:56,779 --> 00:12:59,943
You don't have to work at it, you know, shall I help or not?

127
00:13:00,144 --> 00:13:01,645
It's just there, you want to do it.

128
00:13:02,547 --> 00:13:11,336
And if a friend is successful in something, one rejoices in their success, in their happiness.

129
00:13:11,620 --> 00:13:16,285
And so method is that default position.

130
00:13:17,206 --> 00:13:21,253
So that's why the Buddha puts a lot of stress to it.

131
00:13:28,581 --> 00:13:37,594
These qualities, and we need to add a fourth one called equanimity, which we'll come to in a minute, are considered to be illimitables.

132
00:13:38,029 --> 00:13:44,995
by which we mean that there are a limitable number of beings, so there's no way you can stop at some point and say, well, I've done enough.

133
00:13:45,937 --> 00:13:51,001
And also, in terms of our development within ourselves, it's indefinite.

134
00:13:51,522 --> 00:13:53,764
Developing love is a bit like counting.

135
00:13:54,144 --> 00:13:56,527
No matter how big your number is, you can always add one.

136
00:13:57,106 --> 00:14:01,291
So it's not a case of thinking that you ever come to an end of developing matter.

137
00:14:01,311 --> 00:14:05,774
It just grows and grows and grows, you know, until you become a great charismatic leader, you see.

138
00:14:06,429 --> 00:14:09,592
and then thousands will follow you.

139
00:14:09,613 --> 00:14:15,337
I'm trying to develop that.

140
00:14:15,357 --> 00:14:16,118
Must try harder.

141
00:14:20,162 --> 00:14:25,505
They're also called the Brahma-Viharas, so the Vihara dwelling place of the highest gods, you see.

142
00:14:25,586 --> 00:14:29,850
This is the most beautiful states that we can create within the mind.

143
00:14:30,490 --> 00:14:35,695
So they're the most beautiful states that we can create within ourselves, these particular states.

144
00:14:36,011 --> 00:14:43,620
And so the Buddha equates them to the most beautiful of places, the bountiful heart and the beautiful mind.

145
00:14:47,102 --> 00:15:00,197
Equanimity is, what equanimity is, is trying to come from a place of no judgment.

146
00:15:00,986 --> 00:15:16,546
It's like you're completely opening up to the person as they are and not allowing judgment to distort your ability to receive what the person has to offer, even if it's negative stuff.

147
00:15:18,048 --> 00:15:30,403
So that equanimity is based upon a certain calmness and a certain understanding that if you want to engage with people, then first of all you have to be completely open to them

148
00:15:30,940 --> 00:15:42,836
And that's often a fearful thing for us because we think we're going to be overtaken or somehow controlled if we do that.

149
00:15:45,119 --> 00:15:55,732
But in a sense you can't give a proper response unless you've listened and felt what the other person has to give you, you see.

150
00:15:56,354 --> 00:16:08,653
When we're listening, for instance, to somebody, if you catch these politicians, I don't know about you, but you can hear yourself saying, a lot of rubbish, and they're lying as usual.

151
00:16:09,134 --> 00:16:14,825
And it's a case of that you come from these set positions which we never question.

152
00:16:15,605 --> 00:16:19,511
And we're doing it all the time because the judgmental mind is always with us.

153
00:16:20,433 --> 00:16:22,277
But it's recognizing that it's there,

154
00:16:22,561 --> 00:16:33,894
and then just putting it to the side, and just opening up, you see, and letting the other person express themselves into your mind and heart, and not feeling that that's a sort of takeover bit.

155
00:16:34,715 --> 00:16:38,840
And to do that, you have to have this position of equanimity.

156
00:16:38,879 --> 00:16:48,871
And because you're equanimous, you see, although you're feeling and understanding, it's not actually entering into you.

157
00:16:49,527 --> 00:16:55,496
because your base is equanimity, you're not reacting, you're not saying yes, yes, yes or no, no, no, see?

158
00:16:55,517 --> 00:17:03,571
And because of that little gap which equanimity creates, you're able to respond rather than react, that's all.

159
00:17:04,010 --> 00:17:08,598
So whenever you're coming from a position, you're necessarily reacting, see?

160
00:17:08,848 --> 00:17:20,603
But if you take no position, if you're completely open, then there's a much better way of understanding what the person is saying, what the person is trying to communicate.

161
00:17:22,505 --> 00:17:28,551
And this allows for genuine communication, which again is part of metta, you see.

162
00:17:28,892 --> 00:17:37,422
So equanimity, and that's what we'll be practicing when I'm finally done, just to develop this very open, spacious awareness.

163
00:17:42,987 --> 00:18:12,605
the practice is basically the use of a mantra, a verse or sentences which are meaningful to us now the four classic ones the four usual ones that are used are may you be safe

164
00:18:13,867 --> 00:18:15,210
Everybody wants to be safe.

165
00:18:15,410 --> 00:18:19,634
They want to be safe from dangers outside themselves, but dangers from within ourselves.

166
00:18:19,914 --> 00:18:25,040
Dangers, you know, safe from economic crises for a start.

167
00:18:25,520 --> 00:18:33,651
So it's a case of recognizing that safety is really the basic platform for human existence.

168
00:18:33,730 --> 00:18:34,832
Everybody wants to be safe.

169
00:18:35,633 --> 00:18:37,394
When we're safe, then we feel we can

170
00:18:37,595 --> 00:18:41,039
you know, we're free to do, you see.

171
00:18:41,059 --> 00:18:44,744
So, offering people safety, may you be safe.

172
00:18:45,365 --> 00:18:47,108
The next thing is physical health.

173
00:18:47,229 --> 00:18:48,309
Everybody wants to be healthy.

174
00:18:49,172 --> 00:18:50,113
So may you be well.

175
00:18:50,733 --> 00:18:51,835
The next one is happy.

176
00:18:52,175 --> 00:18:54,618
Everybody wants to be happy, you know, free of distress.

177
00:18:56,461 --> 00:19:05,474
And the final one is to have an ease of living, you know, which is very difficult in our times today.

178
00:19:05,741 --> 00:19:15,615
But that's really something which allows us to have a deep sense of happiness if we have ease of living, in whichever way you want to describe that.

179
00:19:16,276 --> 00:19:20,942
It could be economic ease, it could be social ease, it could be relationship ease.

180
00:19:21,403 --> 00:19:27,791
It's just that the ease of living allows us to live in harmony.

181
00:19:28,393 --> 00:19:33,960
So it's partly to do with an attitude of contentment.

182
00:19:34,565 --> 00:19:40,250
which is more about wanting what you get rather than always trying to get what you want.

183
00:19:41,132 --> 00:19:43,733
And it's being content to what one has.

184
00:19:43,773 --> 00:19:46,237
It doesn't stop one also having aspirations.

185
00:19:47,017 --> 00:20:04,555
So to be contented and to live in harmony, even when the person you're trying to be harmonious with is not particularly in tune with you, the point is that you're always trying to find this nice, this peaceful, this ease, even with people whom you don't get on with

186
00:20:06,981 --> 00:20:08,904
So those are your four blessings.

187
00:20:10,007 --> 00:20:19,701
And you have to take your time with them because they have to be meaningful in terms of their deliberate well-wishings.

188
00:20:20,001 --> 00:20:23,307
They're not like when you pass people and you say, how are you doing?

189
00:20:23,327 --> 00:20:24,009
I'm doing all right.

190
00:20:24,048 --> 00:20:24,829
Cheers, okay.

191
00:20:26,432 --> 00:20:28,455
Which is just a social pleasantry.

192
00:20:29,036 --> 00:20:35,165
When I started doing this sort of practice, I went to work one morning and I actually said,

193
00:20:35,450 --> 00:20:37,792
to a colleague who was coming down the corridor.

194
00:20:37,813 --> 00:20:39,034
I said, how are you?

195
00:20:39,394 --> 00:20:44,420
And I obviously said it in a way that made him think, well, this guy's really interested.

196
00:20:44,460 --> 00:20:47,583
So he kept me for 10 minutes telling me how he was, you see.

197
00:20:48,063 --> 00:20:49,945
And I got late for my class.

198
00:20:50,266 --> 00:20:54,509
So then I thought, no, this is not the time to really ask people how they are.

199
00:20:55,991 --> 00:20:57,874
So there's nothing wrong with pleasantries.

200
00:20:58,334 --> 00:21:04,461
It's just that what we're doing here is actually really meaning, meaning, meaning it, you see.

201
00:21:04,744 --> 00:21:10,569
not just the passing hello.

202
00:21:14,869 --> 00:21:20,096
Also, when we're doing it, we're doing it for the benefit of the other.

203
00:21:20,916 --> 00:21:23,339
Of course, we do turn it towards ourselves.

204
00:21:23,839 --> 00:21:30,827
But when you say, may so-and-so be happy, may so-and-so be well, may so-and-so be safe, well and happy.

205
00:21:30,847 --> 00:21:36,575
When you're saying that, you are meaning for them to be happy, for them to be safe.

206
00:21:37,615 --> 00:21:39,357
It's not like a throwaway line.

207
00:21:39,827 --> 00:21:50,239
So, if you can image the person in your mind, it doesn't have to be a strong visualization, you know, and re-establish some relationship with that person, and you're offering them that goodwill.

208
00:21:50,679 --> 00:22:05,193
Now, whether it touches them or not, over space and time, well, maybe, you know, some people say it does, but in terms of our practice, that's not relevant, because what we're doing is just developing the inner heart, see?

209
00:22:05,950 --> 00:22:06,713
That's what we're doing.

210
00:22:07,035 --> 00:22:12,702
So that when we meet the person, hopefully they'll see it, they'll feel it.

211
00:22:35,650 --> 00:22:37,491
I'll come to that other stuff a bit later on.

212
00:22:38,373 --> 00:22:44,678
So let me just go through very quickly, because we'll do it as a practice at the end of the evening.

213
00:22:45,058 --> 00:22:46,799
So we start with the benefactor.

214
00:22:47,201 --> 00:22:55,268
And over the first at least half day, try and work with, it could be just one benefactor.

215
00:22:55,288 --> 00:22:58,191
You don't have to seek hundreds of thousands of them.

216
00:22:58,211 --> 00:23:02,895
But you could actually just go through your life and realize how many people have helped you in your life.

217
00:23:03,756 --> 00:23:05,438
And every time you think of somebody,

218
00:23:05,619 --> 00:23:07,142
you know, offer them these blessings.

219
00:23:08,683 --> 00:23:12,971
It's good to start with somebody whom you don't have any problems with, if you can find somebody.

220
00:23:16,234 --> 00:23:18,659
It just helps, you know, to start at an easy base.

221
00:23:19,200 --> 00:23:20,862
And then you can sort of extend it.

222
00:23:22,084 --> 00:23:25,429
An uncomplicated relationship.

223
00:23:25,449 --> 00:23:31,096
Somebody who, when you think of them, naturally warms the heart, you see.

224
00:23:31,116 --> 00:23:33,400
Now, having said that...

225
00:23:34,240 --> 00:23:58,372
this metta practice is working even when you have no feelings in the heart, even when your heart, your emotional life, you know, is dull, is dead, is not responding, it might be depressed, it might even be bored, you see, it doesn't matter, you keep, as it were, meaning these phrases, you see, and eventually the heart will begin to resonate with those phrases.

226
00:23:59,554 --> 00:24:01,175
Now,

227
00:24:02,032 --> 00:24:07,159
It doesn't mean to say that just because we're practicing metta, we won't be suffering all the hindrances.

228
00:24:08,340 --> 00:24:09,982
They will definitely come up.

229
00:24:10,383 --> 00:24:11,825
So there'll be wandering mind.

230
00:24:12,286 --> 00:24:13,507
Your mind will start planning.

231
00:24:13,586 --> 00:24:16,431
It'll be thinking about past things, future things.

232
00:24:16,451 --> 00:24:20,174
It'll be suddenly you're saying, may you be safe, may you be well.

233
00:24:20,596 --> 00:24:23,358
And you're off, you're strangling somebody.

234
00:24:23,839 --> 00:24:26,864
See, then you know there's aversion.

235
00:24:27,023 --> 00:24:31,128
Then you suddenly fall asleep and you're walking around like a zombie.

236
00:24:31,378 --> 00:24:35,489
And then you can't handle it anymore because you're so restless and your mind's all over the place.

237
00:24:36,131 --> 00:24:37,875
And then you start having doubts.

238
00:24:37,915 --> 00:24:39,038
Well, this is no good for me.

239
00:24:39,098 --> 00:24:40,362
I can't be bothered doing this.

240
00:24:40,422 --> 00:24:41,163
It's a waste of time.

241
00:24:41,464 --> 00:24:46,317
So all these, you know, the hindrances, Mara, the evil one, will definitely arise.

242
00:24:46,786 --> 00:25:15,527
but what we do is with these is unlike in vipassana where we actually work with them here we just park them now make a distinction here between pushing something away with aversion or fear which is suppressing, which is not doing us any good and just saying I'll handle you another time you're just gently parking them and then you bring your attention back to what you're doing and then you find that they're all waiting for you next weekend you see

243
00:25:15,962 --> 00:25:23,513
So it's not that they go away, but you're not adding any aggressive, any aggression into the system, okay?

244
00:25:24,013 --> 00:25:34,548
So you're very kind, you say, now that's a bit of hate, you know, I see you there, you see, I just, you hang on there for a minute, you see, okay, you know, we'll deal with you afterwards, and you keep back and practice metta.

245
00:25:34,749 --> 00:25:41,818
Now, let me give you an image which I've got from Asajoli, and some of you may know the Italian therapist.

246
00:25:41,838 --> 00:25:43,741
He uses it in a different sense, but it's a good image.

247
00:25:44,009 --> 00:25:51,657
So if you think of the mind like an egg, the bottom part is all nicely fully developed, you see.

248
00:25:52,159 --> 00:25:57,925
So that's our usual stuff, you know, the stuff that we've developed both negative and positive.

249
00:25:58,426 --> 00:26:03,792
But the top bit, the top part of the egg is sort of slopes away and needs to be blown out a bit.

250
00:26:04,153 --> 00:26:07,738
So what we're doing is we are developing the beautiful side of the mind.

251
00:26:08,258 --> 00:26:12,221
But remember that in so doing, we're not treating with the underneath of the egg.

252
00:26:13,301 --> 00:26:15,544
That, as it were, remains untreated.

253
00:26:15,604 --> 00:26:22,590
But at least the mind on top of this swamp is actually growing and becoming beautiful.

254
00:26:23,711 --> 00:26:25,873
And it's a strengthening thing.

255
00:26:26,193 --> 00:26:36,762
So that when you come to practice vipassana, those of you who've done it, you can actually imbue your investigation with kindness, you see.

256
00:26:37,080 --> 00:27:06,125
you can actually give it a flavor of kindness as things come up inside you but for the purpose of this course we're just going to park the stuff you see deal with it another time now sometimes of course it is it does come up and it just you can't get rid of it I mean it's just full in your face in which case if you haven't done Vipassana then come and tell me and I'll give you a few hints before you run away and

257
00:27:06,358 --> 00:27:08,501
If you do, then do vipassana on it.

258
00:27:09,021 --> 00:27:13,508
Just sit with it in vipassana, you see, and wait for it to pass, wait for it to pass.

259
00:27:13,528 --> 00:27:16,832
And as soon as it begins to pass, just park it and start again.

260
00:27:17,492 --> 00:27:23,240
And in that way, on a longest retreat, you can actually develop this metta with vipassana.

261
00:27:23,421 --> 00:27:27,726
And they both actually are very supportive to each other, very supportive.

262
00:27:30,877 --> 00:27:38,769
So we begin with the benefactor and then usually we move to a dear friend.

263
00:27:38,989 --> 00:27:43,075
Again, not too complicated a relationship.

264
00:27:43,095 --> 00:27:45,117
And then to a neutral person.

265
00:27:45,719 --> 00:27:47,582
You can bring in, of course, family.

266
00:27:48,363 --> 00:27:51,467
You can bring in pets, you know what I mean.

267
00:27:51,487 --> 00:27:54,912
Dogs and cats deserve a bit of love.

268
00:27:54,932 --> 00:27:58,557
And then finally, at some point tomorrow,

269
00:27:58,907 --> 00:28:28,459
while you're doing the benefactor also guide that loving-kindness towards yourself so when we remember a benefactor we remember the good things they did for us so we begin by thinking about the good things we've done in our lives yeah and as you remember one thing that you've done which may be just to open the door for somebody doesn't have to be some huge heroic act as you remember that then you offer yourself the blessing you see

270
00:28:28,944 --> 00:28:34,549
So we're building up a very positive image of ourselves in connection with the benefactor.

271
00:28:35,411 --> 00:28:51,986
And then we begin to introduce into our practice these other people, those who are near and dear, dear friends, neutral people, people whom we see probably every day almost on the way to work, neighbors whom we see but we don't know.

272
00:28:52,026 --> 00:28:58,951
And we begin to offer the same goodwill towards those people.

273
00:28:59,219 --> 00:29:27,825
space outwards in a more general way and we'll go through that this evening to ourselves to our neighbours there you can relocate you don't have to do neighbours around here and then to the country to all people in Europe all people on earth and all beings in all directions so eventually the heart is just opening out to develop an attitude so this is what metta is

274
00:29:28,260 --> 00:29:32,805
You're developing an attitude of goodwill no matter who stands in front of you.

275
00:29:33,465 --> 00:29:35,788
That's the point.

276
00:29:35,807 --> 00:29:45,136
So whatever being stands in front of you, there's an immediate good-hearted relationship set up from your side toward them.

277
00:29:45,156 --> 00:29:47,199
And that's what we mean by universal.

278
00:29:47,500 --> 00:29:50,362
And that's sometimes you get this non-attachment.

279
00:29:50,382 --> 00:29:55,247
You'll find the word detached used, which tends to be misunderstood.

280
00:29:55,648 --> 00:29:58,211
Other people are using the word non-attachment.

281
00:29:58,311 --> 00:30:03,857
But all that means is that your goodwill is not dependent on whether you like the person or not.

282
00:30:04,077 --> 00:30:04,458
That's all.

283
00:30:06,840 --> 00:30:19,074
And then it becomes universal, you see.

284
00:30:19,094 --> 00:30:19,954
I think that's enough of that.

285
00:30:20,675 --> 00:30:20,855
Yes?

286
00:30:21,557 --> 00:30:21,977
Very good.

287
00:30:23,662 --> 00:30:28,630
Any immediate questions about that?

288
00:30:28,710 --> 00:30:33,417
I'm just curious that you don't include the animal, the difficult person, as a stage.

289
00:30:33,999 --> 00:30:34,700
Yeah, I will do.

290
00:30:35,280 --> 00:30:36,123
I will do, yeah.

291
00:30:39,107 --> 00:30:44,076
In a sense, that comes with the forgiving as well, the forgivingness that we do on the third day.

292
00:30:49,625 --> 00:30:50,226
Something, when you said about

293
00:30:51,876 --> 00:31:11,998
Do you mean specifically towards the benefactor?

294
00:31:13,759 --> 00:31:19,385
You don't mean reflecting on your good deeds generally, you just mean towards the benefactor?

295
00:31:20,057 --> 00:31:24,684
No, what I'm suggesting is that I might think of somebody who's done me good.

296
00:31:25,766 --> 00:31:25,987
Right?

297
00:31:26,027 --> 00:31:30,192
So I then offer that person my goodwill.

298
00:31:30,212 --> 00:31:30,432
See?

299
00:31:31,134 --> 00:31:33,738
And then I might think of something that I've done good.

300
00:31:34,298 --> 00:31:36,682
And then I say, may I be well, may I be happy.

301
00:31:37,523 --> 00:31:39,547
So there's a connection there.

302
00:31:41,609 --> 00:31:41,710
Yeah.

303
00:31:41,730 --> 00:31:41,829
Yeah.

304
00:31:43,784 --> 00:31:52,034
And as I say, don't make the mistake of judging your metta by the emotional value that arises.

305
00:31:53,776 --> 00:31:54,817
That can be a big mistake.

306
00:31:55,178 --> 00:32:01,585
And the other big mistake is that once you start feeling beautiful within yourself, you start doing it for that reason.

307
00:32:02,405 --> 00:32:03,948
So you do your metta in order to feel good.

308
00:32:04,328 --> 00:32:07,192
So then you become a do-gooder, which is a terrible thing.

309
00:32:09,434 --> 00:32:11,557
So be careful of that.

310
00:32:11,656 --> 00:32:13,098
Take it more, it's a gift.

311
00:32:13,432 --> 00:32:13,693
See?

312
00:32:13,933 --> 00:32:20,508
So suddenly you're landed with this very beautiful state within your heart, and it's very lovely and peaceful, etc., etc.

313
00:32:20,768 --> 00:32:23,755
So receive that as a gift, you see, but don't do it for that reason.

314
00:32:24,415 --> 00:32:27,342
Do it in order to develop a good attitude.

